**Freedom of thought** (*Denkfreiheit*) is the inalienable right Fichte argues princes cannot grant or withdraw. His chain of reasoning in chapter 2: free thought is an "intimate component of personhood" — the very basis of the "I am" — so it is by nature inalienable. Because it could never validly have been surrendered in the social contract, society never held the right to transfer it to a prince. The prince's authority derives only from what society could contractually give him, so he has literally no jurisdiction over it. Fichte states this directly: *"Prince, you have no right to suppress our freedom of thought"* and *"you have no rights whatsoever over our freedom of thought; no decision over what is true or false; no right to determine the objects of our inquiry, or to set its limits."*
